<subSubSection id="C32660E89E039F13FF0DFB47163B1EA7" pageId="12" pageNumber="363" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8333639E039F13FF0DFB47163B1EA7" blockId="12.[151,1437,325,1430]" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B948EF719E039F13FF0DFB4713771E37" bold="true" box="[199,315,1261,1286]" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described from 
<collectingRegion id="49F8FD819E039F13FD0AFB47116D1E37" box="[704,801,1261,1286]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4E929E039F13FC85FB4711F01E37" author="Li" box="[847,956,1261,1286]" pageId="12" pageNumber="363" refString="Li, Z. Z. (1990) Four new species of the genus Scaphoideus (Homoptera: Euscelidae). Acta Zootaxonomia Sinica, 15 (4), 464 - 470. [in Chinese with English summary]" type="journal article" year="1990">Li (1990)</bibRefCitation>
based on three female specimens that are deposited in the Institute of Entomology, 
<collectingRegion id="49F8FD819E039F13FDB0FABB10971E1B" box="[634,731,1297,1322]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
University, 
<collectingCountry id="F32B73F39E039F13FCA1FABB11FE1E1B" box="[875,946,1297,1322]" name="China" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">China</collectingCountry>
. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4E929E039F13FBF8FABB16A81E1B" box="[1074,1252,1297,1322]" pageId="12" pageNumber="363" refString="Li, Z. Z., Dai, R. H. &amp; Xing, J. C. (2011) Deltocephalinae from China (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae). Popular Science Press, Beijing, 336 pp. [in Chinese with English summary]" type="book">
Li 
<emphasis id="B948EF719E039F13FB9FFAB816DC1E18" box="[1109,1168,1297,1321]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="363">et al.</emphasis>
(2011)
</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the species and provided figures of the male genitalia. This species can be distinguished by the short pygofer process at the posterior margin, subapical triangular process of the subgenital plate and by the aedeagal shaft being short and robust, with a pair of short dorsoapical processes subequal to half the length of the shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
